ollowing accident prevention program elements are in place at the Mt. Vernon LP Terminal:

1) Employee Participation;
2) Process Safety Information;
3) Process Hazard Analysis (PHA);
4) Standard Operating Procedures;
5) Training;
6) Contractors;
7) Pre-startup Safety Review;
8) Mechanical Integrity with Preventive Maintenance;
9) Hazardous Work Permits;
10)Management of Change;
11)Incident or Potential Catastrophic Event Investigation;
12)Emergency Response;
13)Compliance Audits; and
14)Trade Secrets.

These fourteen (14) individual elements of this prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases. The Mt. Vernon LP Terminal and its employees are committed to the standards required by these management programs. In addition to the above elements, MPLX also has specific prevention measures that are employed as part of the Terminal's operating procedures and engineering/administrative controls to help prevent, identify, contain/control, and reduce the consequences of a release. These are summarized as follows:

General Risk Reduction and Safety Measures:

-Engineering and construction in accordance with recognized industry and company standards;
-Equipment properly designed with protection from overpressure (pressure safety relief valves, etc.);
-Updated technical drawings, Piping & Instrumentation Diagrams and Process/Block Flow Diagrams;
-Operating systems monitored and controlled by trained Operators;
-Redundant control systems;
-Manual shutdown devices for critical systems;
-Scheduled inspection and testing of safety devices/critical equipment;
-Limited/secured facility access;
-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;
-Routinely scheduled safety inspections and audits; and
-Frequent unit surveillance by operators.

General Release Mitigation:

-Process and remotely operated shut-offs to limit release quantity (also actuated via a fusible element);
-Strategically located valves to isolate leaks; and
